"Parra-Olea G., Martínez-Meyer E., Pérez-Ponce De León G.","Forecasting climate change effects on salamander distribution in the highlands of central Mexico",2005,"Biotropica","37","2",,"202","208",,,10.1111/j.1744-7429.2005.00027.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-20444371605&partnerID=40&md5=61cc099d00ced3974aff70955000075b","Instituto de Biología, Departamento de Zoología, UNAM, AP 70-153, CP 04510, México, D.F., Mexico","Parra-Olea, G., Instituto de Biología, Departamento de Zoología, UNAM, AP 70-153, CP 04510, México, D.F., Mexico; Martínez-Meyer, E., Instituto de Biología, Departamento de Zoología, UNAM, AP 70-153, CP 04510, México, D.F., Mexico; Pérez-Ponce De León, G., Instituto de Biología, Departamento de Zoología, UNAM, AP 70-153, CP 04510, México, D.F., Mexico","A generalized decline of amphibian populations is occurring worldwide. The causes for such a decline are not completely understood; however, climate change has been identified as a possible cause for amphibian extinction, among others. Ecological niche modeling has proven to be a useful tool to predict potential distribution of species in the context of climatic changes. In this paper, we used the Genetic Algorithm for Rule-set Prediction (GARP) to model the potential distributions of two species of plethodontid salamanders: Pseudoeurycea cephalica and P. leprosa. We projected their potential distributions under climatic scenarios expected in 50 yr based on a conservative scenario of global climate change and assuming a moderate dispersal ability for both species. Our analyses suggest that climate change effects may pose an additional long-term risk to both species of plethodontid salamanders, with a more dramatic scenario in the case of P. leprosa. By the year 2050, this species may lose almost 75 percent of its distributional area, and this projection is even worse when deforestation (in the way it is occurring at present) is considered within the predicted model. Our results concur with those obtained for species with limited dispersal capability because they do not track changing climates, but rather face a loss of distributional area. The survival of these species is not secure, even though their potential distributional area falls within a considerable number of natural protected areas.","Amphibian decline; Climate change; Ecological niche modeling; Mexico; Plethodontid salamanders; Pseudoeurycea cephalica; Pseudoeurycea leprosa","amphibian; climate change; ecological modeling; geographical distribution; niche; population decline; Mexico [North America]; North America; Western Hemisphere; World; Amphibia; Amphiuma means; Caudata; Plethodontidae; Pseudoeurycea cephalica; Pseudoeurycea leprosa",,,,,,"Alford, R.A., Richards, S.J., Global amphibian declines: A problem in applied ecology (1999) Ann. Rev. Ecol. Syst., 30, pp. 133-165; Anderson, R.P., Lew, D., Peterson, A.T., Evaluating predictive models of species' distributions: Criteria for selecting optimal models (2003) Ecol. Model., 162, pp. 211-232; Martinez-Meyer, E., Modeling species' geographic distributions for preliminary conservation assessments: An implementation with the spiny pocket mice (Heteromys) of Ecuador (2004) Biol. Conserv., 116, pp. 167-179; Blaustein, A.R., Wake, D.B., Declining amphibian populations: A global phenomenon? (1990) TREE, 5, pp. 203-204; Davis, A.J., Jenkinson, L.S., Lawton, J.H., Shorrocks, B., Wood, S., Making mistakes when predicting shifts in species range in response to global warming (1998) Nature, 391, pp. 783-786; Flato, G.M., Boer, G.J., Warming asymmetry in climate change simulations (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28, pp. 195-198; Flores-Villela, O., Canseco-Márquez, L., Nuevas especies y cambios taxonomicos para la herpetofauna de México (2004) Acta Zool. Mex. (n.s.), 20, pp. 115-144; Grinnell, J., Field tests of theories concerning distributional control (1917) Am. Nat., 51, pp. 115-128; Hill, J.K., Thomas, C.D., Fox, R., Telfer, M.G., Willis